members.name: getTitle
members.comment: The title of a document as specified by the TITLE element in the head of the document.

members.name: getReferrer
members.comment: Returns the URI of the page that linked to this page. The value is an empty string if the user navigated to the page directly (not through a link, but, for example, via a bookmark).

members.name: getDomain
members.comment: The domain name of the server that served the document, or null if the server cannot be identified by a domain name.

members.name: getURL
members.comment: The complete URI of the document.

members.name: getBody
members.comment: The element that contains the content for the document. In documents with BODY contents, returns the BODY element. In frameset documents, this returns the outermost FRAMESET element.

members.name: getImages
members.comment: A collection of all the IMG elements in a document. The behavior is limited to IMG elements for backwards compatibility.

members.name: getApplets
members.comment: A collection of all the OBJECT elements that include applets and APPLET ( deprecated ) elements in a document.

members.name: getLinks
members.comment: A collection of all AREA elements and anchor ( A ) elements in a document with a value for the href attribute.

members.name: getForms
members.comment: A collection of all the forms of a document.

members.name: getAnchors
members.comment: A collection of all the anchor (A ) elements in a document with a value for the name attribute. Note. For reasons of backwards compatibility, the returned set of anchors only contains those anchors created with the name attribute, not those created with the id attribute.

members.name: getCookie
members.comment: The cookies associated with this document. If there are none, the value is an empty string. Otherwise, the value is a string: a semicolon-delimited list of "name, value" pairs for all the cookies associated with the page. For example, name=value;expires=date .

members.name: open
members.comment: Note. This method and the ones following allow a user to add to or replace the structure model of a document using strings of unparsed HTML. At the time of writing alternate methods for providing similar functionality for both HTML and XML documents were being considered. The following methods may be deprecated at some point in the future in favor of a more general-purpose mechanism. Open a document stream for writing. If a document exists in the target, this method clears it.

members.name: close
members.comment: Closes a document stream opened by open() and forces rendering.

members.name: write
members.comment: Write a string of text to a document stream opened by open() . The text is parsed into the document's structure model.

param: text - The string to be parsed into some structure in the document structure model.

members.name: writeln
members.comment: Write a string of text followed by a newline character to a document stream opened by open() . The text is parsed into the document's structure model.

param: text - The string to be parsed into some structure in the document structure model.

members.name: getElementsByName
members.comment: Returns the (possibly empty) collection of elements whose name value is given by elementName .

param: elementName - The name attribute value for an element.
